<title>INDIA: India's NSE replaces six firms in 50-stock index.</title>
<headline>India's NSE replaces six firms in 50-stock index.</headline>
<dateline>BOMBAY 1996-09-10</dateline>
<text>
<p>India's National Stock Exchange (NSE) said on Tuesday it will replace six firms in its 50-stock index to make it more representative.</p>
<p>&quot;A revision of this nature in the composition of securities included in the NSE-50 has become essential to make the index as highly scientic and representative as possible,&quot; the NSE said in a statement.</p>
<p>The NSE has decided to include Mahindra &amp; Mahindra, Nestle, Asea Brown Boveri, East India Hotels, Asian Paints and Glaxo.</p>
<p>It will remove Indian Aluminium, Chambal Fertilisers, Nagarjun Fertiliser, Apollo Tyres, Hero Honda and Madras Refineries.</p>
<p>The six additions have a total market capitalisation of 138.79 billion rupees. The six stocks which are being removed have a market capitalisation of only 36.88 billion rupees, the NSE said.</p>
<p>The changes become effective from September 18.</p>
<p>The NSE plans to introduce what it terms a Dollar Nifty, or Defty, index which will the dollar equivalent of the NSE-50 index. It also proposes a NSE Mid-Cap index.</p>
